Beautiful, intimate and inspiring Armenian Orthodox Church. Very good reception otherwise. Very comfortable seats so as not to spoil anything.

St John the Baptist Cathedral was built between 1902 and 1904 on the orders of benefactor Alexander Montashev, originally from Tbilisi in Georgia. The land housed a large wooden warehouse which hosted the Charit√© bazaar for a few months before burning down in 1897. Place of contemplation, peaceful where one emerges peaceful.

Currently under renovation, but we cannot miss this splendid cathedral in the 8th arrondissement. It is the St John the Baptist Cathedral built between 1902 and 1904. A cathedral of the Armenian Apostolic Church which was born from the evangelization of the holy apostles Thaddeus and Bartholomew. It is an oriental and autocephalous Church, part of the group known as "the Churches of the three councils. The Supreme Patriarch and Catholicos of all Armenians who resides in Etchmiadzin near Yerevan enjoys a primacy of honor among the different hierarchs: the current holder is Karekin II since October 27, 1999. The exceptional and symbolic architecture of Armenian cathedrals have influenced other churches in the West and the East. That of John the Baptist testifies to the originality. and the richness of this Armenian art which has lasted for centuries!
United Armenians all over the world under one holy roof.

Historic place of worship of the Armenian Community of Paris. Every Sunday it is celebrated in the Armenian rite, with an excellent choir. A part of the Holy Mass is also recited in French for the non-Armenian faithful or for the young Armenian generations who do not yet know their native language.
